[src:meta-learning/gradient-descent] Gradient descent works in spaces of any number of dimensions, even in infinite-dimensional ones.
[src:meta-learning/gradient-descent] In the latter case, the search space is typically a function space, and one calculates the Fréchet derivative of the functional to be minimized to determine the descent direction.
[src:meta-learning/gradient-descent] That gradient descent works in any number of dimensions (finite number at least) can be seen as a consequence of the Cauchy–Schwarz inequality, i.e. the magnitude of the inner (dot) product of two vectors of any dimension is maximized when they are colinear.
[src:meta-learning/gradient-descent] In the case of gradient descent, that would be when the vector of independent variable adjustments is proportional to the gradient vector of partial derivatives.
[src:meta-learning/gradient-descent] The gradient descent can take many iterations to compute a local minimum with a required accuracy, if the curvature in different directions is very different for the given function.
[src:meta-learning/gradient-descent] For such functions, preconditioning, which changes the geometry of the space to shape the function level sets like concentric circles, cures the slow convergence.
[src:meta-learning/gradient-descent] Constructing and applying preconditioning can be computationally expensive, however.
[src:meta-learning/gradient-descent] The gradient descent can be modified via momentums (Nesterov, Polyak, and Frank–Wolfe) and heavy-ball parameters (exponential moving averages and positive-negative momentum).
[src:meta-learning/gradient-descent] The main examples of such optimizers are Adam, DiffGrad, Yogi, AdaBelief, etc.
[src:meta-learning/gradient-descent] Methods based on Newton's method and inversion of the Hessian using conjugate gradient techniques can be better alternatives.
[src:meta-learning/gradient-descent] Generally, such methods converge in fewer iterations, but the cost of each iteration is higher.
[src:meta-learning/gradient-descent] While it is sometimes possible to substitute gradient descent for a local search algorithm, gradient descent is not in the same family: although it is an iterative method for local optimization, it relies on an objective function's gradient rather than an explicit exploration of a solution space.
[src:meta-learning/gradient-descent] Gradient descent can be viewed as applying Euler's method for solving ordinary differential equations $x'(t)=-\nabla f(x(t))$ to a gradient flow.
[src:meta-learning/gradient-descent] In turn, this equation may be derived as an optimal controller for the control system $x'(t)=u(t)$ with $u(t)$ given in feedback form $u(t)=-\nabla f(x(t))$ .
[src:meta-learning/gradient-descent] Gradient descent can converge to a local minimum and slow down in a neighborhood of a saddle point.
[src:meta-learning/gradient-descent] Even for unconstrained quadratic minimization, gradient descent develops a zig–zag pattern of subsequent iterates as iterations progress, resulting in slow convergence.
[src:meta-learning/gradient-descent] Multiple modifications of gradient descent have been proposed to address these deficiencies.
[src:meta-learning/gradient-descent] Yurii Nesterov has proposed a simple modification that enables faster convergence for convex problems and has been since further generalized.
[src:meta-learning/gradient-descent] For unconstrained smooth problems, the method is called the fast gradient method (FGM) or the accelerated gradient method (AGM).
[src:meta-learning/gradient-descent] Specifically, if the differentiable function f is convex and $\nabla f$ is Lipschitz, and it is not assumed that f is strongly convex, then the error in the objective value generated at each step k by the gradient descent method will be bounded by ${\textstyle {\mathcal {O}}\left({k^{-1}}\right)}$ .
[src:meta-learning/gradient-descent] Using the Nesterov acceleration technique, the error decreases at ${\textstyle {\mathcal {O}}\left({k^{-2}}\right)}$ .
[src:meta-learning/gradient-descent] It is known that the rate ${\mathcal {O}}\left({k^{-2}}\right)$ for the decrease of the cost function is optimal for first-order optimization methods.
[src:meta-learning/gradient-descent] Nevertheless, there is the opportunity to improve the algorithm by reducing the constant factor.
[src:meta-learning/gradient-descent] The optimized gradient method (OGM) reduces that constant by a factor of two and is an optimal first-order method for large-scale problems.
[src:meta-learning/gradient-descent] For constrained or non-smooth problems, Nesterov's FGM is called the fast proximal gradient method (FPGM), an acceleration of the proximal gradient method.
[src:meta-learning/gradient-descent] Gradient descent with momentum remembers the solution update at each iteration, and determines the next update as a linear combination of the gradient and the previous update.
[src:meta-learning/gradient-descent] For unconstrained quadratic minimization, a theoretical convergence rate bound of the heavy ball method is asymptotically the same as that for the optimal conjugate gradient method.
[src:meta-learning/gradient-descent] This technique is used in stochastic gradient descent and as an extension to the backpropagation algorithms used to train artificial neural networks.
[src:meta-learning/gradient-descent] In the direction of updating, stochastic gradient descent adds a stochastic property.
[src:meta-learning/gradient-descent] The weights can be used to calculate the derivatives.
[src:meta-learning/gradient-descent] Gradient descent can be extended to handle constraints by including a projection onto the set of constraints.
[src:meta-learning/gradient-descent] This method is only feasible when the projection is efficiently computable on a computer.
[src:meta-learning/gradient-descent] Under suitable assumptions, this method converges.
[src:meta-learning/gradient-descent] This method is a specific case of the forward–backward algorithm for monotone inclusions (which includes convex programming and variational inequalities).
[src:meta-learning/gradient-descent] Gradient descent is a special case of mirror descent using the squared Euclidean distance as the given Bregman divergence.
[src:meta-learning/gradient-descent] The properties of gradient descent depend on the properties of the objective function and the variant of gradient descent used (for example, if a line search step is used).
[src:meta-learning/gradient-descent] The assumptions made affect the convergence rate, and other properties, that can be proven for gradient descent.
[src:meta-learning/gradient-descent] For example, if the objective is assumed to be strongly convex and lipschitz smooth, then gradient descent converges linearly with a fixed step size.
[src:meta-learning/gradient-descent] Looser assumptions lead to either weaker convergence guarantees or require a more sophisticated step size selection.
[src:meta-learning/meta-learning-computer-science] Flexibility is important because each learning algorithm is based on a set of assumptions about the data, its inductive bias.
[src:meta-learning/meta-learning-computer-science] This means that it will only learn well if the bias matches the learning problem.
[src:meta-learning/meta-learning-computer-science] A learning algorithm may perform very well in one domain, but not on the next.
[src:meta-learning/meta-learning-computer-science] This poses strong restrictions on the use of machine learning or data mining techniques, since the relationship between the learning problem (often some kind of database) and the effectiveness of different learning algorithms is not yet understood.
[src:meta-learning/meta-learning-computer-science] Critiques of meta-learning approaches bear a strong resemblance to the critique of metaheuristic, a possibly related problem.
[src:meta-learning/meta-learning-computer-science] A good analogy to meta-learning, and the inspiration for Jürgen Schmidhuber's early work (1987) and Yoshua Bengio et al.'s work (1991), considers that genetic evolution learns the learning procedure encoded in genes and executed in each individual's brain.
[src:meta-learning/meta-learning-computer-science] In an open-ended hierarchical meta-learning system using genetic programming, better evolutionary methods can be learned by meta evolution, which itself can be improved by meta meta evolution, etc.
[src:meta-learning/meta-learning-computer-science] 3. explicitly optimizing model parameters for fast learning (optimization-based).
[src:meta-learning/meta-learning-computer-science] Model-based meta-learning models updates its parameters rapidly with a few training steps, which can be achieved by its internal architecture or controlled by another meta-learner model.
[src:meta-learning/meta-learning-computer-science] A Memory-Augmented Neural Network, or MANN for short, is claimed to be able to encode new information quickly and thus to adapt to new tasks after only a few examples.
[src:meta-learning/meta-learning-computer-science] Meta Networks (MetaNet) learns a meta-level knowledge across tasks and shifts its inductive biases via fast parameterization for rapid generalization.
[src:meta-learning/meta-learning-computer-science] The core idea in metric-based meta-learning is similar to nearest neighbors algorithms, which weight is generated by a kernel function.
[src:meta-learning/meta-learning-computer-science] It aims to learn a metric or distance function over objects.
[src:meta-learning/meta-learning-computer-science] The notion of a good metric is problem-dependent.
[src:meta-learning/meta-learning-computer-science] It should represent the relationship between inputs in the task space and facilitate problem solving.
[src:meta-learning/meta-learning-computer-science] Siamese neural network is composed of two twin networks whose output is jointly trained.
[src:meta-learning/meta-learning-computer-science] There is a function above to learn the relationship between input data sample pairs.
[src:meta-learning/meta-learning-computer-science] The two networks are the same, sharing the same weight and network parameters.
[src:meta-learning/meta-learning-computer-science] Matching Networks learn a network that maps a small labelled support set and an unlabelled example to its label, obviating the need for fine-tuning to adapt to new class types.
[src:meta-learning/meta-learning-computer-science] The Relation Network (RN), is trained end-to-end from scratch.
[src:meta-learning/meta-learning-computer-science] During meta-learning, it learns to learn a deep distance metric to compare a small number of images within episodes, each of which is designed to simulate the few-shot setting.
[src:meta-learning/meta-learning-computer-science] Prototypical Networks learn a metric space in which classification can be performed by computing distances to prototype representations of each class.
[src:meta-learning/meta-learning-computer-science] Compared to recent approaches for few-shot learning, they reflect a simpler inductive bias that is beneficial in this limited-data regime, and achieve satisfied results.
[src:meta-learning/meta-learning-computer-science] What optimization-based meta-learning algorithms intend for is to adjust the optimization algorithm so that the model can be good at learning with a few examples.
[src:meta-learning/meta-learning-computer-science] LSTM-based meta-learner is to learn the exact optimization algorithm used to train another learner neural network classifier in the few-shot regime.
[src:meta-learning/meta-learning-computer-science] The parametrization allows it to learn appropriate parameter updates specifically for the scenario where a set amount of updates will be made, while also learning a general initialization of the learner (classifier) network that allows for quick convergence of training.
[src:meta-learning/meta-learning-computer-science] Model-Agnostic Meta-Learning (MAML) is a fairly general optimization algorithm, compatible with any model that learns through gradient descent.
[src:meta-learning/meta-learning-computer-science] Reptile is a remarkably simple meta-learning optimization algorithm, given that both of its components rely on meta-optimization through gradient descent and both are model-agnostic.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] In machine learning (ML), **feature learning** or **representation learning** is a set of techniques that allow a system to automatically discover the representations needed for feature detection or classification from raw data.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] This replaces manual feature engineering and allows a machine to both learn the features and use them to perform a specific task.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] Feature learning is motivated by the fact that ML tasks such as classification often require input that is mathematically and computationally convenient to process.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] However, real-world data, such as image, video, and sensor data, have not yielded to attempts to algorithmically define specific features.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] An alternative is to discover such features or representations through examination, without relying on explicit algorithms.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] Supervised feature learning is learning features from labeled data.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] The data label allows the system to compute an error term, the degree to which the system fails to produce the label, which can then be used as feedback to correct the learning process (reduce/minimize the error).
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] Dictionary learning develops a set (dictionary) of representative elements from the input data such that each data point can be represented as a weighted sum of the representative elements.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] The dictionary elements and the weights may be found by minimizing the average representation error (over the input data), together with *L1* regularization on the weights to enable sparsity (i.e., the representation of each data point has only a few nonzero weights).
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] Supervised dictionary learning exploits both the structure underlying the input data and the labels for optimizing the dictionary elements.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] For example, this supervised dictionary learning technique applies dictionary learning on classification problems by jointly optimizing the dictionary elements, weights for representing data points, and parameters of the classifier based on the input data.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] Neural networks are a family of learning algorithms that use a "network" consisting of multiple layers of inter-connected nodes.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] It is inspired by the animal nervous system, where the nodes are viewed as neurons and edges are viewed as synapses.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] Each edge has an associated weight, and the network defines computational rules for passing input data from the network's input layer to the output layer.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] A network function associated with a neural network characterizes the relationship between input and output layers, which is parameterized by the weights.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] With appropriately defined network functions, various learning tasks can be performed by minimizing a cost function over the network function (weights).
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] Multilayer neural networks can be used to perform feature learning, since they learn a representation of their input at the hidden layer(s) which is subsequently used for classification or regression at the output layer.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] The most popular network architecture of this type is Siamese networks.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] Unsupervised feature learning is learning features from unlabeled data.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] The goal of unsupervised feature learning is often to discover low-dimensional features that capture some structure underlying the high-dimensional input data.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] When the feature learning is performed in an unsupervised way, it enables a form of semisupervised learning where features learned from an unlabeled dataset are then employed to improve performance in a supervised setting with labeled data.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] Several approaches are introduced in the following.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] K-means clustering can be used to group an unlabeled set of inputs into *k* clusters, and then use the centroids of these clusters to produce features.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] These features can be produced in several ways.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] The simplest is to add *k* binary features to each sample, where each feature *j* has value one iff the *j*th centroid learned by *k*-means is the closest to the sample under consideration.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] It is also possible to use the distances to the clusters as features, perhaps after transforming them through a radial basis function (a technique that has been used to train RBF networks).
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] Coates and Ng note that certain variants of *k*-means behave similarly to sparse coding algorithms.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] In a comparative evaluation of unsupervised feature learning methods, Coates, Lee and Ng found that *k*-means clustering with an appropriate transformation outperforms the more recently invented auto-encoders and RBMs on an image classification task.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] *K*-means also improves performance in the domain of NLP, specifically for named-entity recognition; there, it competes with Brown clustering, as well as with distributed word representations (also known as neural word embeddings).
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] Principal component analysis (PCA) is often used for dimension reduction.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] Equivalently, these singular vectors are the eigenvectors corresponding to the *p* largest eigenvalues of the sample covariance matrix of the input vectors.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] These *p* singular vectors are the feature vectors learned from the input data, and they represent directions along which the data has the largest variations.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] PCA is a linear feature learning approach since the *p* singular vectors are linear functions of the data matrix.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] The singular vectors can be generated via a simple algorithm with *p* iterations.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] In the *i*th iteration, the projection of the data matrix on the *(i-1)*th eigenvector is subtracted, and the *i*th singular vector is found as the right singular vector corresponding to the largest singular of the residual data matrix.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] First, it assumes that the directions with large variance are of most interest, which may not be the case.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] PCA only relies on orthogonal transformations of the original data, and it exploits only the first- and second-order moments of the data, which may not well characterize the data distribution.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] Furthermore, PCA can effectively reduce dimension only when the input data vectors are correlated (which results in a few dominant eigenvalues).
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] Local linear embedding (LLE) is a nonlinear learning approach for generating low-dimensional neighbor-preserving representations from (unlabeled) high-dimension input.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] The approach was proposed by Roweis and Saul (2000).
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] The general idea of LLE is to reconstruct the original high-dimensional data using lower-dimensional points while maintaining some geometric properties of the neighborhoods in the original data set.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] The second step is for "dimension reduction," by looking for vectors in a lower-dimensional space that minimizes the representation error using the optimized weights in the first step.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] Note that in the first step, the weights are optimized with fixed data, which can be solved as a least squares problem.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] In the second step, lower-dimensional points are optimized with fixed weights, which can be solved via sparse eigenvalue decomposition.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] The reconstruction weights obtained in the first step capture the "intrinsic geometric properties" of a neighborhood in the input data.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] It is assumed that original data lie on a smooth lower-dimensional manifold, and the "intrinsic geometric properties" captured by the weights of the original data are also expected to be on the manifold.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] This is why the same weights are used in the second step of LLE.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] Compared with PCA, LLE is more powerful in exploiting the underlying data structure.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] Independent component analysis (ICA) is a technique for forming a data representation using a weighted sum of independent non-Gaussian components.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] The assumption of non-Gaussian is imposed since the weights cannot be uniquely determined when all the components follow Gaussian distribution.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] Unsupervised dictionary learning does not utilize data labels and exploits the structure underlying the data for optimizing dictionary elements.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] An example of unsupervised dictionary learning is sparse coding, which aims to learn basis functions (dictionary elements) for data representation from unlabeled input data.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] Sparse coding can be applied to learn overcomplete dictionaries, where the number of dictionary elements is larger than the dimension of the input data.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] Aharon et al. proposed algorithm K-SVD for learning a dictionary of elements that enables sparse representation.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] The hierarchical architecture of the biological neural system inspires deep learning architectures for feature learning by stacking multiple layers of learning nodes.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] These architectures are often designed based on the assumption of distributed representation: observed data is generated by the interactions of many different factors on multiple levels.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] In a deep learning architecture, the output of each intermediate layer can be viewed as a representation of the original input data.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] Each level uses the representation produced by the previous, lower level as input, and produces new representations as output, which are then fed to higher levels.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] The input at the bottom layer is raw data, and the output of the final, highest layer is the final low-dimensional feature or representation.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] Restricted Boltzmann machines (RBMs) are often used as a building block for multilayer learning architectures.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] An RBM can be represented by an undirected bipartite graph consisting of a group of binary hidden variables, a group of visible variables, and edges connecting the hidden and visible nodes.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] It is a special case of the more general Boltzmann machines with the constraint of no intra-node connections.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] Each edge in an RBM is associated with a weight.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] The weights together with the connections define an energy function, based on which a joint distribution of visible and hidden nodes can be devised.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] Based on the topology of the RBM, the hidden (visible) variables are independent, conditioned on the visible (hidden) variables.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] Such conditional independence facilitates computations.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] An RBM can be viewed as a single layer architecture for unsupervised feature learning.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] In particular, the visible variables correspond to input data, and the hidden variables correspond to feature detectors.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] The weights can be trained by maximizing the probability of visible variables using Hinton's contrastive divergence (CD) algorithm.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] In general, training RBMs by solving the maximization problem tends to result in non-sparse representations.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] Sparse RBM was proposed to enable sparse representations.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] The idea is to add a regularization term in the objective function of data likelihood, which penalizes the deviation of the expected hidden variables from a small constant p .
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] RBMs have also been used to obtain *disentangled* representations of data, where interesting features map to separate hidden units.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] An autoencoder consisting of an encoder and a decoder is a paradigm for deep learning architectures.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] An example is provided by Hinton and Salakhutdinov where the encoder uses raw data (e.g., image) as input and produces feature or representation as output and the decoder uses the extracted feature from the encoder as input and reconstructs the original input raw data as output.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] The encoder and decoder are constructed by stacking multiple layers of RBMs.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] The parameters involved in the architecture were originally trained in a greedy layer-by-layer manner: after one layer of feature detectors is learned, they are fed up as visible variables for training the corresponding RBM.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] Current approaches typically apply end-to-end training with stochastic gradient descent methods.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] Training can be repeated until some stopping criteria are satisfied.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] Self-supervised representation learning is learning features by training on the structure of unlabeled data rather than relying on explicit labels for an information signal.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] This approach has enabled the combined use of deep neural network architectures and larger unlabeled datasets to produce deep feature representations.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] Training tasks typically fall under the classes of either contrastive, generative or both.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] Contrastive representation learning trains representations for associated data pairs, called positive samples, to be aligned, while pairs with no relation, called negative samples, are contrasted.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] A larger portion of negative samples is typically necessary in order to prevent catastrophic collapse, which is when all inputs are mapped to the same representation.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] Generative representation learning tasks the model with producing the correct data to either match a restricted input or reconstruct the full input from a lower dimensional representation.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] A common setup for self-supervised representation learning of a certain data type (e.g. text, image, audio, video) is to pretrain the model using large datasets of general context, unlabeled data.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] Depending on the context, the result of this is either a set of representations for common data segments (e.g. words) which new data can be broken into, or a neural network able to convert each new data point (e.g. image) into a set of lower dimensional features.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] In either case, the output representations can then be used as an initialization in many different problem settings where labeled data may be limited.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] Specialization of the model to specific tasks is typically done with supervised learning, either by fine-tuning the model / representations with the labels as the signal, or freezing the representations and training an additional model which takes them as an input.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] Many self-supervised training schemes have been developed for use in representation learning of various modalities, often first showing successful application in text or image before being transferred to other data types.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] Word2vec is a word embedding technique which learns to represent words through self-supervision over each word and its neighboring words in a sliding window across a large corpus of text.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] The model has two possible training schemes to produce word vector representations, one generative and one contrastive.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] The first is word prediction given each of the neighboring words as an input.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] The second is training on the representation similarity for neighboring words and representation dissimilarity for random pairs of words.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] A limitation of word2vec is that only the pairwise co-occurrence structure of the data is used, and not the ordering or entire set of context words.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] More recent transformer-based representation learning approaches attempt to solve this with word prediction tasks.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] GPTs pretrain on next word prediction using prior input words as context, whereas BERT masks random tokens in order to provide bidirectional context.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] Other self-supervised techniques extend word embeddings by finding representations for larger text structures such as sentences or paragraphs in the input data.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] Doc2vec extends the generative training approach in word2vec by adding an additional input to the word prediction task based on the paragraph it is within, and is therefore intended to represent paragraph level context.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] The domain of image representation learning has employed many different self-supervised training techniques, including transformation, inpainting, patch discrimination and clustering.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] Many other self-supervised methods use siamese networks, which generate different views of the image through various augmentations that are then aligned to have similar representations.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] The challenge is avoiding collapsing solutions where the model encodes all images to the same representation.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] SimCLR is a contrastive approach which uses negative examples in order to generate image representations with a ResNet CNN.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] Bootstrap Your Own Latent (BYOL) removes the need for negative samples by encoding one of the views with a slow moving average of the model parameters as they are being modified during training.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] Another approach is to maximize mutual information, a measure of similarity, between the representations of associated structures within the graph.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] An example is Deep Graph Infomax, which uses contrastive self-supervision based on mutual information between the representation of a "patch" around each node, and a summary representation of the entire graph.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] Negative samples are obtained by pairing the graph representation with either representations from another graph in a multigraph training setting, or corrupted patch representations in single graph training.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] With analogous results in masked prediction and clustering, video representation learning approaches are often similar to image techniques but must utilize the temporal sequence of video frames as an additional learned structure.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] Examples include VCP, which masks video clips and trains to choose the correct one given a set of clip options, and Xu et al., who train a 3D-CNN to identify the original order given a shuffled set of video clips.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] Self-supervised representation techniques have also been applied to many audio data formats, particularly for speech processing.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] Wav2vec 2.0 discretizes the audio waveform into timesteps via temporal convolutions, and then trains a transformer on masked prediction of random timesteps using a contrastive loss.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] This is similar to the BERT language model, except as in many SSL approaches to video, the model chooses among a set of options rather than over the entire word vocabulary.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] Self-supervised learning has also been used to develop joint representations of multiple data types.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] Approaches usually rely on some natural or human-derived association between the modalities as an implicit label, for instance video clips of animals or objects with characteristic sounds, or captions written to describe images.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] CLIP produces a joint image-text representation space by training to align image and text encodings from a large dataset of image-caption pairs using a contrastive loss.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] Multimodal representation models are typically unable to assume direct correspondence of representations in the different modalities, since the precise alignment can often be noisy or ambiguous.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] For example, the text "dog" could be paired with many different pictures of dogs, and correspondingly a picture of a dog could be captioned with varying degrees of specificity.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] This limitation means that downstream tasks may require an additional generative mapping network between modalities to achieve optimal performance, such as in DALLE-2 for text to image generation.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] Dynamic representation learning methods generate latent embeddings for dynamic systems such as dynamic networks.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] Since particular distance functions are invariant under particular linear transformations, different sets of embedding vectors can actually represent the same/similar information.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] Therefore, for a dynamic system, a temporal difference in its embeddings may be explained by misalignment of embeddings due to arbitrary transformations and/or actual changes in the system.
[src:meta-learning/representation-learning] Therefore, generally speaking, temporal embeddings learned via dynamic representation learning methods should be inspected for any spurious changes and be aligned before consequent dynamic analyses.
[src:meta-learning/supervised-learning] In machine learning, **supervised learning** (**SL**) is a type of machine learning paradigm where an algorithm learns to map input data to a specific output based on example input-output pairs.
[src:meta-learning/supervised-learning] This process involves training a statistical model using labeled data, meaning each piece of input data is provided with the correct output.
[src:meta-learning/supervised-learning] The term "supervised" refers to the role of a teacher or supervisor who provides this training data, guiding the algorithm towards correct predictions.
[src:meta-learning/supervised-learning] For instance, if you want a model to identify cats in images, supervised learning would involve feeding it many images of cats (inputs) that are explicitly labeled "cat" (outputs).
[src:meta-learning/supervised-learning] The goal of supervised learning is for the trained model to accurately predict the output for new, unseen data.
[src:meta-learning/supervised-learning] This requires the algorithm to effectively generalize from the training examples, a quality measured by its *generalization error*.
[src:meta-learning/supervised-learning] Supervised learning is commonly used for tasks like classification (predicting a category, e.g., spam or not spam) and regression (predicting a continuous value, e.g., house prices).
[src:meta-learning/supervised-learning] The training set needs to be representative of the real-world use of the function.
[src:meta-learning/supervised-learning] Thus, a set of input objects is gathered together with corresponding outputs, either from human experts or from measurements.
[src:meta-learning/supervised-learning] Determine the input feature representation of the learned function.
[src:meta-learning/supervised-learning] The accuracy of the learned function depends strongly on how the input object is represented.
[src:meta-learning/supervised-learning] Typically, the input object is transformed into a feature vector, which contains a number of features that are descriptive of the object.
[src:meta-learning/supervised-learning] The number of features should not be too large, because of the curse of dimensionality; but should contain enough information to accurately predict the output.
[src:meta-learning/supervised-learning] Determine the structure of the learned function and corresponding learning algorithm.
[src:meta-learning/supervised-learning] For example, one may choose to use support-vector machines or decision trees.
[src:meta-learning/supervised-learning] Run the learning algorithm on the gathered training set.
[src:meta-learning/supervised-learning] Some supervised learning algorithms require the user to determine certain control parameters.
[src:meta-learning/supervised-learning] These parameters may be adjusted by optimizing performance on a subset (called a *validation set*) of the training set, or via cross-validation.
[src:meta-learning/supervised-learning] Evaluate the accuracy of the learned function.
[src:meta-learning/supervised-learning] After parameter adjustment and learning, the performance of the resulting function should be measured on a test set that is separate from the training set.
[src:meta-learning/supervised-learning] A wide range of supervised learning algorithms are available, each with its strengths and weaknesses.
[src:meta-learning/supervised-learning] There is no single learning algorithm that works best on all supervised learning problems (see the No free lunch theorem).
[src:meta-learning/supervised-learning] A first issue is the tradeoff between *bias* and *variance*.
[src:meta-learning/supervised-learning] Imagine that we have available several different, but equally good, training data sets.
[src:meta-learning/supervised-learning] A learning algorithm is biased for a particular input x if, when trained on each of these data sets, it is systematically incorrect when predicting the correct output for x .
[src:meta-learning/supervised-learning] A learning algorithm has high variance for a particular input x if it predicts different output values when trained on different training sets.
[src:meta-learning/supervised-learning] The prediction error of a learned classifier is related to the sum of the bias and the variance of the learning algorithm.
[src:meta-learning/supervised-learning] Generally, there is a tradeoff between bias and variance.
[src:meta-learning/supervised-learning] A learning algorithm with low bias must be "flexible" so that it can fit the data well.
[src:meta-learning/supervised-learning] But if the learning algorithm is too flexible, it will fit each training data set differently, and hence have high variance.
[src:meta-learning/supervised-learning] A key aspect of many supervised learning methods is that they are able to adjust this tradeoff between bias and variance (either automatically or by providing a bias/variance parameter that the user can adjust).
[src:meta-learning/supervised-learning] The second issue is of the amount of training data available relative to the complexity of the "true" function (classifier or regression function).
[src:meta-learning/supervised-learning] If the true function is simple, then an "inflexible" learning algorithm with high bias and low variance will be able to learn it from a small amount of data.
[src:meta-learning/supervised-learning] A third issue is the dimensionality of the input space.
[src:meta-learning/supervised-learning] If the input feature vectors have large dimensions, learning the function can be difficult even if the true function only depends on a small number of those features.
[src:meta-learning/supervised-learning] This is because the many "extra" dimensions can confuse the learning algorithm and cause it to have high variance.
[src:meta-learning/supervised-learning] Hence, input data of large dimensions typically requires tuning the classifier to have low variance and high bias.
[src:meta-learning/supervised-learning] In practice, if the engineer can manually remove irrelevant features from the input data, it will likely improve the accuracy of the learned function.
[src:meta-learning/supervised-learning] In addition, there are many algorithms for feature selection that seek to identify the relevant features and discard the irrelevant ones.
[src:meta-learning/supervised-learning] This is an instance of the more general strategy of dimensionality reduction, which seeks to map the input data into a lower-dimensional space prior to running the supervised learning algorithm.
[src:meta-learning/supervised-learning] A fourth issue is the degree of noise in the desired output values (the supervisory target variables).
[src:meta-learning/supervised-learning] If the desired output values are often incorrect (because of human error or sensor errors), then the learning algorithm should not attempt to find a function that exactly matches the training examples.
[src:meta-learning/supervised-learning] Attempting to fit the data too carefully leads to overfitting.
[src:meta-learning/supervised-learning] You can overfit even when there are no measurement errors (stochastic noise) if the function you are trying to learn is too complex for your learning model.
[src:meta-learning/supervised-learning] In such a situation, the part of the target function that cannot be modeled "corrupts" your training data – this phenomenon has been called deterministic noise.
[src:meta-learning/supervised-learning] When either type of noise is present, it is better to go with a higher bias, lower variance estimator.
[src:meta-learning/supervised-learning] In practice, there are several approaches to alleviate noise in the output values such as early stopping to prevent overfitting as well as detecting and removing the noisy training examples prior to training the supervised learning algorithm.
[src:meta-learning/supervised-learning] There are several algorithms that identify noisy training examples and removing the suspected noisy training examples prior to training has decreased generalization error with statistical significance.
[src:meta-learning/supervised-learning] When considering a new application, the engineer can compare multiple learning algorithms and experimentally determine which one works best on the problem at hand (see cross-validation).
[src:meta-learning/supervised-learning] Tuning the performance of a learning algorithm can be very time-consuming.
[src:meta-learning/supervised-learning] Given fixed resources, it is often better to spend more time collecting additional training data and more informative features than it is to spend extra time tuning the learning algorithms.
[src:meta-learning/supervised-learning] Given a set of N training examples of the form $\{(x_{1},y_{1}),...,(x_{N},\;y_{N})\}$ such that $x_{i}$ is the feature vector of the i -th example and $y_{i}$ is its label (i.e., class), a learning algorithm seeks a function $g:X\to Y$ , where X is the input space and Y is the output space.
[src:meta-learning/supervised-learning] The function g is an element of some space of possible functions G , usually called the *hypothesis space*.
[src:meta-learning/supervised-learning] It is sometimes convenient to represent g using a scoring function $f:X\times Y\to \mathbb {R}$ such that g is defined as returning the y value that gives the highest score: $g(x)={\underset {y}{\arg \max }}\;f(x,y)$ .
[src:meta-learning/supervised-learning] Let F denote the space of scoring functions.
[src:meta-learning/supervised-learning] Although G and F can be any space of functions, many learning algorithms are probabilistic models where g takes the form of a conditional probability model $g(x)={\underset {y}{\arg \max }}\;P(y|x)$ , or f takes the form of a joint probability model $f(x,y)=P(x,y)$ .
[src:meta-learning/supervised-learning] For example, naive Bayes and linear discriminant analysis are joint probability models, whereas logistic regression is a conditional probability model.
[src:meta-learning/supervised-learning] There are two basic approaches to choosing f or g : empirical risk minimization and structural risk minimization.
[src:meta-learning/supervised-learning] Empirical risk minimization seeks the function that best fits the training data.
[src:meta-learning/supervised-learning] Structural risk minimization includes a *penalty function* that controls the bias/variance tradeoff.
[src:meta-learning/supervised-learning] In both cases, it is assumed that the training set consists of a sample of independent and identically distributed pairs, $(x_{i},\;y_{i})$ .
[src:meta-learning/supervised-learning] In order to measure how well a function fits the training data, a loss function $L:Y\times Y\to \mathbb {R} ^{\geq 0}$ is defined.
[src:meta-learning/supervised-learning] The *risk* $R(g)$ of function g is defined as the expected loss of g .
[src:meta-learning/supervised-learning] In empirical risk minimization, the supervised learning algorithm seeks the function g that minimizes $R(g)$ .
[src:meta-learning/supervised-learning] Hence, a supervised learning algorithm can be constructed by applying an optimization algorithm to find g .
[src:meta-learning/supervised-learning] When g is a conditional probability distribution $P(y|x)$ and the loss function is the negative log likelihood: $L(y,{\hat {y}})=-\log P(y|x)$ , then empirical risk minimization is equivalent to maximum likelihood estimation.
[src:meta-learning/supervised-learning] When G contains many candidate functions or the training set is not sufficiently large, empirical risk minimization leads to high variance and poor generalization.
[src:meta-learning/supervised-learning] The learning algorithm is able to memorize the training examples without generalizing well (overfitting).
[src:meta-learning/supervised-learning] Structural risk minimization seeks to prevent overfitting by incorporating a regularization penalty into the optimization.
[src:meta-learning/supervised-learning] The regularization penalty can be viewed as implementing a form of Occam's razor that prefers simpler functions over more complex ones.
[src:meta-learning/supervised-learning] A wide variety of penalties have been employed that correspond to different definitions of complexity.
[src:meta-learning/supervised-learning] A popular regularization penalty is $\sum _{j}\beta _{j}^{2}$ , which is the squared Euclidean norm of the weights, also known as the $L_{2}$ norm.
[src:meta-learning/supervised-learning] Other norms include the $L_{1}$ norm, $\sum _{j}|\beta _{j}|$ , and the $L_{0}$ "norm", which is the number of non-zero $\beta _{j}$ s.
[src:meta-learning/supervised-learning] The parameter $\lambda$ controls the bias-variance tradeoff.
[src:meta-learning/supervised-learning] When $\lambda =0$ , this gives empirical risk minimization with low bias and high variance.
[src:meta-learning/supervised-learning] When $\lambda$ is large, the learning algorithm will have high bias and low variance.
[src:meta-learning/supervised-learning] The value of $\lambda$ can be chosen empirically via cross-validation.
[src:meta-learning/supervised-learning] The complexity penalty has a Bayesian interpretation as the negative log prior probability of g , $-\log P(g)$ , in which case $J(g)$ is the posterior probability of g .
[src:meta-learning/supervised-learning] The training methods described above are *discriminative training* methods, because they seek to find a function g that discriminates well between the different output values (see discriminative model).
[src:meta-learning/supervised-learning] Generative training algorithms are often simpler and more computationally efficient than discriminative training algorithms.
[src:meta-learning/supervised-learning] In some cases, the solution can be computed in closed form as in naive Bayes and linear discriminant analysis.
[src:meta-learning/transfer-learning] Since transfer learning makes use of training with multiple objective functions it is related to cost-sensitive machine learning and multi-objective optimization.
[src:meta-learning/transfer-learning] In 1976, Bozinovski and Fulgosi published a paper addressing transfer learning in neural network training.
[src:meta-learning/transfer-learning] The paper gives a mathematical and geometrical model of the topic.
[src:meta-learning/transfer-learning] In 1981, a report considered the application of transfer learning to a dataset of images representing letters of computer terminals, experimentally demonstrating positive and negative transfer learning.
[src:meta-learning/transfer-learning] In 1992, Lorien Pratt formulated the discriminability-based transfer (DBT) algorithm.
[src:meta-learning/transfer-learning] By 1998, the field had advanced to include multi-task learning, along with more formal theoretical foundations.
[src:meta-learning/transfer-learning] Influential publications on transfer learning include the book *Learning to Learn* in 1998, a 2009 survey and a 2019 survey.
[src:meta-learning/transfer-learning] Ng said in his NIPS 2016 tutorial that TL would become the next driver of machine learning commercial success after supervised learning.
[src:meta-learning/transfer-learning] In the 2020 paper, "Rethinking Pre-Training and self-training", Zoph et al. reported that pre-training can hurt accuracy, and advocate self-training instead.
[src:meta-learning/transfer-learning] The definition of transfer learning is given in terms of domains and tasks.
[src:meta-learning/transfer-learning] A domain ${\mathcal {D}}$ consists of: a feature space ${\mathcal {X}}$ and a marginal probability distribution $P(X)$ , where $X=\{x_{1},...,x_{n}\}\in {\mathcal {X}}$ .
[src:meta-learning/transfer-learning] Given a specific domain, ${\mathcal {D}}=\{{\mathcal {X}},P(X)\}$ , a task consists of two components: a label space ${\mathcal {Y}}$ and an objective predictive function $f:{\mathcal {X}}\rightarrow {\mathcal {Y}}$ .
[src:meta-learning/transfer-learning] The function f is used to predict the corresponding label $f(x)$ of a new instance x .
[src:meta-learning/transfer-learning] Algorithms for transfer learning are available in Markov logic networks and Bayesian networks.
[src:meta-learning/transfer-learning] Transfer learning has been applied to cancer subtype discovery, building utilization, general game playing, text classification, digit recognition, medical imaging and spam filtering.
[src:meta-learning/transfer-learning] It was noted that this relationship worked in both directions, showing that EEG brainwaves can likewise be used to classify EMG signals.
[src:meta-learning/transfer-learning] The experiments noted that the accuracy of neural networks and convolutional neural networks were improved through transfer learning both prior to any learning (compared to standard random weight distribution) and at the end of the learning process (asymptote).
[src:meta-learning/transfer-learning] That is, results are improved by exposure to another domain.
[src:meta-learning/transfer-learning] Moreover, the end-user of a pre-trained model can change the structure of fully-connected layers to improve performance.
